<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Habinteg</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Habinteg</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Habinteg welcomes the opportunity to respond to the House of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Commons Work and Pensions Select Committee’s inquiry into the ‘provision of support to meet housing costs in the reformed welfare system’. This response concentrates particularly on the implications of changes to support for housing costs for disabled peop</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">le and, in particular, Habinteg tenants. We take into account changes as a result of the introduction of Universal Credit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (UC)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and other changes to housing support costs. We also respond to the committee’s request for information on the implications of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> changes for housing providers, and for information on responses to the changes. As a housing provider, Habinteg presents information drawn from our own experience.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About Habinteg</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Habinteg is a housing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">association</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with more than 40 years’ experience pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">viding homes and services to disabled and non-disabled tenants. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Habinteg champions inclusion by working to:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nfluence policy and promote good practice in relation to inclusive, accessible housing and independent living for disabled people;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rovide a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd strengthen research expertise and guidance on all aspects of housing and disability;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nform the development of new ventures in areas such as: housing options and advice; supply of accessible homes; inclusive design in housing and neighbourhoods; effecti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ve home adaptations; support to individuals and families.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The social model of disability is crucial to every aspect of Habinteg’s work. We believe that people are disabled by barriers in society and negative public attitudes, rather than by their own </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">impairments.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Habinteg operates across </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">more than</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 80 local authorities in England and Wales and manages over 3,300 homes. Of these more than 1,200 are designed for wheelchair users with the rest being designed to Lifetime Homes standards. Over 59 per ce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nt of our tenants (April 2012) tell us that they define themselves as disabled people.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Disabled people and housing cost – context</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To appreciate fully the impact of reductions in support for housing costs on disabled people it is important to understand </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the context in which these cuts are taking place. This particularly means the housing needs and housing-related costs of disabled people. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We draw attention to the following:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overnment statistics show that there are currently more than eleven million di</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sabled people in Great Britain</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he number of older disabled people in England is projected to grow from approximately 2.3 million in 2002 to approximately 4.6 million in 2041, an increase of 98%</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">isabled people face higher costs of living than non-di</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sabled people: one recent large scale survey estimate the average such cost at just under £100 per week, amounting to 50 per cent of their weekly income</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Significant parts of these costs are housing related, such as the cost of adapting inaccessible housi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng and requiring a particular size and types of accommod</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ation to accommodate impairment. Only about 27 per cent of those estimated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by this survey, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to face disability-related costs, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">we</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">re in receipt of disability-related cash benefits.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Di</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sabled people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">remain significantly less likely to be in employment than non-disabled people</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, are more likely to be excluded from school</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and are less likely to hold formal qualifications than non-disabled people</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Disabled people are significantly less likely to live i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n households with access to the internet than non-disabled people: in 2011 61 per cent of disabled people lived in households with internet access, compared to 86 per cent of non-disabled people. Such figures reflect and entrench the greater levels of pove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rty found among disabled people.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Habinteg research over many years confirms that there is a high percentage of disabled people living in inaccessible properties or who wait many years for an accessible property:  data from 2007/08 showed there were then a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t least 78,300 wheelchair user households in England with unmet housing needs, amounting to at least 240 households in an average local authority; many tenants who take up Habinteg properties have waited up to 10 years for a wheelchair accessible property;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> one in five disabled people requiring adaptations to their home believe that their accommodation is not suitable</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and 145,000 disabled people aged 65 and over report living in homes that do not meet their needs</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One in three households</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">disabled person live in non-decent accommodation</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While accessible housing, with the ability to move around and use safely all parts of one’s home, is crucial to independent living, so is the wider environment. Disabled people also often need and want to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> live close to established areas and networks which support their independence. This includes proximity to family and friends and to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">particular travel modes and routes and to services and employment. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Policies that force people to move</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> can be particularly d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">evastating for disabled people.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The consultation</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Habinteg believes that current changes to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">support f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> housing costs will further impoverish disabled people. In particular, they threaten to render important aspects of housing unaffordable. They will also place real strains on the ability of housing providers to meet the needs of disabled people.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Bedroom </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Tax </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We firstly address the issue of the bedroom tax.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Disabled people and bedroom tax</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The government’s own equality impact assessment of the spare room subsidy policy accepted that the majority of those affected by a cut to Housing Benefit via this rout</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e would be disabled people</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and that the average financial loss would be £14 a week across the total 660,000 people affected. The decision to continue on with this policy despite this evidence of disproportionate impact seems perverse. The ‘bedroom tax’ ru</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">le that Housing Benefit will be reduced by 14 per cent if a person is deemed to have one bedroom too many and by 25 per cent if two or more bedrooms has been subject to a number of challenges by disabled people</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. As a result, room space above the criteria </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">can continue to be covered by Housing Benefit in certain circumstances, specifically where it can be demonstrated through medical evidence that disabled children require an additional bedroom or where a disabled person requires space for an overnight carer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (but only where that person is not their spouse). This left disabled adults unable to share a room because of disability or who needed additional space still subject to the bedroom tax. Tribunal hearings in Scotland during September 2013</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, however, agreed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with disabled adult claimants that their ‘spare’ rooms were too small to count as bedrooms and space was needed for reasons linked to impairment. Although these rulings do not constitute a legal precedent, they are important legal indications and point to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the strong feeling that the bedroom tax is unworkable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and unfair</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Impact on Habinteg tenants</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Habinteg has around 553 households in properties that will be subject to the under-occupancy rule. Of these, 240 are wheelchair standard properties. Therefore </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of all properties and tenants affected by the under-occupancy rule and who will experience a cut in housing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">support</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Habinteg estimates that 43 per cent are wheelchair accessible properties. This does not mean that only 43 per cent of those </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Habinteg tenant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">who will experience a financial loss are disabled people, as many </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">people living in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> other properties will also be disabled people. However, it is important to identify the particular impact on those tenants in properties specifically designed for wheelcha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ir users as such properties are in very short supply. As stated above, Habinteg tenants occupying wheelchair accessible properties have often waited several years before finding suitable accommodation. If tenants are forced to leave their current homes bec</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ause they are unable to afford the rent, the prospect of finding small wheelchair accessible properties is limited.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Financial impact – arrears </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The impact of the bedroom tax on Habinteg tenants was felt quickly in the form of increased rent arrears. Over</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">all Habinteg has a very good record in collecting rents and supporting tenants to keep arrears low</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. At the time of writing Habinteg is in the process of updating its data on arrears</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> so can only give limited figures at present. On this basis we are able to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> identify an increase in arrears </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of £</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">8,058 by those tenants identified as under-occupying under benefit rules in the four months between April and July 2012.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Habinteg’s response to the changes</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Habinteg does not agree with the bedroom tax. As a response t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o housing shortage it fails to recognise that alternative smaller properties are often simply not available, while treating tenants in receipt of Housing Benefit differently from other tenants. We are particularly concerned about the policy’s disproportion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ate impact on disabled people and introduction apparently without thought or understanding of why disabled people may need more space in their home. However, while making our concerns known – including by engagement with inquiries such as this – we are obl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iged to work with the policy. In this context, Habinteg, while lobbying against the policy, has taken a number of steps to help tenants faced with a cut in Housing Benefit as a result of the bedroom tax. This has included:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Awareness raising measures, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">using newsletters to tenants, posters and leaflets to make tenants aware of forthcoming benefit changes and encouraging them to ‘talk to us’;</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Personal staff visits to all tenants thought to be potentially deemed as ‘under-occupying’ to discuss the benefit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> change and how they might cope; data from these visits has been used to clarify Habinteg’s tenant profile and enhance our understanding of the potential financial impact of the bedroom tax on the organisation.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.45pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Helping tenants to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> try to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> move to a smaller </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">property if requested. However, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the waiting list for transfers is much higher than the number of successful transfers. Between 1 April and 25 September this year 66 transfer requests were added to our existing waiting list for transfers. This is 16 more th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an in the same period last year. From the total waiting list </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for transfers, between 1 April and 25 September 2013, there were only 18 internal transfers.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Applying to local authorities to grant exempt status for Habinteg properties (as Habinteg provides su</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pport services to tenants), which would mean that such properties would sit outside of Universal Credit;</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Where exempt status is denied, we have been supporting tenants to apply for financial support from local authorities in the form of Discretionary Hous</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing Payment (DHP). </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Outcome of responses</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The outcome of these steps is mixed. As identified above, arrears have risen and it is too early to be clear on the exact trend and how far</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> rising arrears can be limited.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At the time of writing Habinteg has been o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bliged to serve notice on 12 tenants in arrears purely attributable to the bedroom tax. We are very aware that many</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Habinteg tenants </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> subject to the compound effect of multiple cuts to benefits</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, some still to come into effect,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the significance o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f lost income through the bedroom tax has to be understood in the context of these. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With regard to exempt status, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">516</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of approximately 1200 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Habinteg </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wheelchair accessible standard </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">properties have so far been granted exempt status by loc</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">al authorities. As</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> this decision is made by individual local authorities, however, results vary, with households and properties in very similar positions being granted exempt status in one authority but denied in another. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some local authorities are only considering exemptio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n in relation to under-occupation status, requiring further applications to be attempted for other circumstances when appropriate. This leaves households in an insecure position. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With regard to DHP, as these applications are made by the tenant not the ho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">using provider, we have less complete data on the outcomes. Again, however, we are aware of extreme variation in the result of applications. Tenants with very similar circumstances have been granted time limited DHP in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">one authority and refused in another</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Research by Papworth Trust found that one in three disabled applicants were being refused DHP</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DHP is also temporary and again this leaves households in an insecure position.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.1.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Impact on Habinteg</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Habinteg’s survival – and its continued ability to provide and promote accessible housing – depends on its rental income. Rising arrears will present the organisation with unpalatable options: increasing rents for all tenants; evicting tenants (even those </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">who may not previously have been in arrears and who try hard to pay their rent); accumulating debt and placing the organisation at unacceptable risk. Habinteg has had to allocate very significant resources to helping tenants understand and cope with the be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">droom tax, and other changes to housing support. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Service charges and Universal Credit</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Changes introduced under Universal Credit threaten to impact negatively on the independence, mobility and health of disabled people. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Disabled people and service char</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ges</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">New guidance issued by the Department for Work and Pensions  render</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> service charges for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">maintenance of disability related aids and adaptations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ineligible for repayment through U</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Ineligible service charges specifically include: ‘Installation, maint</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">enance or repair of any special equipment or adaptations to the tenant’s accommodation in respect of disability or infirmity of tenants’</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. A service contract is essential to ensure that aids and adaptations (e.g. through-floor lifts, stairlifts, hoists, do</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or openers, specialist baths) are kept in good working order and are safe to use. Removing service charges from repayment will have a very serious impact on many disabled people. It may make such equipment unaffordable and thereby severely limit mobility, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">independence within the home and ability to carry out carry out personal care and domestic tasks.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> As well as the potential financial implications, s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uch changes may have both negative physical and psychological impacts.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The guidance changes what has been t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he established practice whereby service charges were recouped under Housing Benefit. The DWP suggests that service charges can be funded through grant funding, such as Disabled Facilities Grants</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (DFGs)</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. However, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">many DFG grants do not include a maintenance element and even if such an element is included it is time limited, with the maximum period being five years in our experience. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Even if an individual’s DFG included funding for that period, thereafter there woul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d be no funding and responsibility would move to the individual. It must be remembered that research shows that current need for adaptations funding outstrips DFG funds by a ratio of about ten to one</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Habinteg, like other housing associations, provides fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r servicing as part of risk management in order to ensure that equipment stays safe and thereby tenants and any carers or assistants are safe in operating equipment. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Impact on Habinteg tenants</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">U</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has yet to be rolled out, and these changes to the fundin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g of service charges will impact on Habinteg tenants piecemeal if/when they transfer to UC. What we know at the moment is that Habinteg currently has 1427 properties subject to service charges for relevant equipment. It is not uncommon for properties to ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ve multiple items. The service charges range from 55p per week to £31.33 per week. These charges cover such things as periodic health and safety testing and servicing, some of which is mandatory, and insurance cover. It does not include minor adaptations w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ork and general responsive maintenance, which are covered by rent. It is easy to see from this range of charges that if funding is removed and tenants have to find money to pay, arrears could rise rapidly. Tenants might decide to go </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">without adaptations, as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">k for adaptations to be removed, or try to risk not maintaining equipment. All these options pose tenants with risk and limits to their independence, safety and health.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Financial impact </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The total annual amount due to Habinteg of service charges is £223,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">000 plus 15 per cent on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cost. From this it is clear that if UC removes the service charges’ funding that was available under Housing Benefit th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ere</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is a major threat to housing providers as well as disabled people. The impact on Habinteg stands out quite dr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">amatically as our housing is delivered on a mainstream model, with disabled and non-disabled tenants living independently in our housing. At the same time, because our homes are accessible and there is a dire shortage of accessible housing, a large proport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ion of our tenants are disabled. Due to this it is possible to see clearly the impact of this change on disabled people, and the impact on housing providers.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.2.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Habinteg’s response to the changes</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Habinteg has strongly argued against the new guidance, engagi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng with the consultation in January 2013, meeting with DWP officials and liaising with others in the sector. We have devoted significant resources to clarifying our exact financial information and discussions are on-going on handling the impact of this ret</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rograde step, should it proceed. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have also taken some early awareness raising steps about this sensitive and difficult issue. The change was raised at Habinteg’s National Tenant Forum and at the organisation’s Homes and Services Committee, which has t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">enant representation. Information has featured in publications to tenants.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Habinteg i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s strongly opposed to limiting benefits that are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> essential for maintaining vital aids and adaptations. As already outlined, these aids support the independence of disable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d people. In the process they secure cost-effective alternatives to expensive residential care. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Habinteg strongly urges the Work and Pensions Committee to do all it can to raise awareness of this change, its likely impact on the independence and choice of disabled people, and request ministers to reconsider.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.3 Direct payment of housing costs to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> tenants</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The direct payment of housing costs to tenants has raised concerns among housing organisations, domestic abuse organisations and disability organisations, among others, about the potential for exploitation, victimisation and increased debt. Habin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">teg shares these concerns and is taking efforts to support tenants and to try to limit the growth of arrears. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.3.1 Habinteg asked those tenants in receipt of Housing Benefit how they would prefer to receive it – direct to them or to Habinteg. From this,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 83 per cent said they would like </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">payments to continue to be made to Habinteg, with only 8 per cent choosing payment to them</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.3.3 While we have major concerns about the impact of direct payments in increasing debt, triggering evictions and escalating </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">individual and household problems, we have worked hard to ensure that tenants are supported in advance of the changes. Habinteg has been:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Working to raise awareness of the changes among tenants through information at appropriate tenant forums, in publicat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ions and in one to one contact via staff and tenants;</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Supporting tenants, where necessary, to set up basic bank accounts;</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Encouraging tenants to set up direct debit facilities;</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Localised Council Tax Support</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Localisation of Council Tax Support will cre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ate a postcode lottery. Instead of standard criteria that apply across the UK, it will mean that a person with a particular set of circumstances will be considered too poor to pay Council Tax in one area but well-off enough in another area. According to th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e Joseph Rowntree Foundation, 2.4 million low-income families will pay on average £138 more in council tax in the year 2013/14</span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Impact on Habinteg tenants</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Habinteg has partial information collected from visits to and contact with tenants, but does not yet have comprehensive data on the impact of localisation of council tax support. We are concerned that localisation, alongside a 10 per cent cut in funding fr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">om central government to local authorities, will mean that many people who previously received support will not do so and that this will cause hardship. We estimate that many tenants who previously had support will have to find between £3 and £6 a week for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Council Tax. Again, this change will take place alongside other reductions in income due to benefit cuts and restrictions in eligibility. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Financial impact </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It will be some time before we can aggregate data and calculate the impact of this particular cu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t on Habinteg in the form of arrears etc.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Habinteg’s response</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As with other changes, Habinteg has embarked on a programme of awareness raising combined with practical support.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The impact of changes to housing support outlined here represent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> intensified hardship and inequality for disabled people in particular. Habinteg is concerned about the impact on all its tenants in receipt of benefit, but wish to draw the Committee’s attention to the added impact that policies such as the bedroom tax an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d the cuts to funding of service charges for disability adaptations will have on the lives of disabled people.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Habinteg would be happy to discuss these matters further with the Committee and hopes that the information provided is useful. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">26 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://odi.dwp.gov.uk/disability-statistics-and-research/disability-facts-and-figures.php#gd"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://odi.dwp.gov.uk/disability-statistics-and-research/disability-facts-and-figures.php#gd</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.pssru.ac.uk/pdf/rs035.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.pssru.ac.uk/pdf/rs035.pdf</span></a></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="https://www.iser.essex.ac.uk/publications/working-papers/iser/2012-09.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.iser.essex.ac.uk/publications/working-papers/iser/2012-09.pdf</span></